Good. Now let me implement the changes.

### Change 1: Refactor buildGroupsSystemPrompt to use shared helpers

Current:
```typescript
function buildGroupsSystemPrompt(config: PiAutocommitConfig): string {
  const lang = isJapanese(config) ? "ja" : "en";
  const scopeManaged = hasScopeMapping(config);

  const subjectLangInstruction =
    lang === "ja"
      ? "Write the subject in Japanese (日本語). No period, 50 chars or fewer."
      : "English, imperative present tense, lowercase, no period, 50 chars or fewer.";

  const bodyLangInstruction =
    lang === "ja"
      ? "Write the body in Japanese (日本語)."
      : "Write the body in English.";
  ...
  `Subject: ${subjectLangInstruction}`,
  `Body: describe what changed and why. ${bodyLangInstruction}`,
```

Change to use helpers:
```typescript
function buildGroupsSystemPrompt(config: PiAutocommitConfig): string {
  const scopeManaged = hasScopeMapping(config);
  const subjectFormat = scopeManaged
    ? "Subject format: `type: brief summary` — do NOT add a scope; the scope is applied automatically from the changed paths."
    : "Subject format: `type(scope): brief summary`";

  const rules = [
    ...
    subjectFormat,
    `Subject: ${subjectLangInstruction(config)}`,
    `Body: describe what changed and why. ${bodyLangInstruction(config)}`,
    ...
  ];
```

Wait, the body instruction in buildGroupsSystemPrompt says "Body: describe what changed and why. {bodyLangInstruction}". The helper `bodyLangInstruction` returns "Write the body in English." So the combined string would be "Body: describe what changed and why. Write the body in English." This matches current behavior.

For subject, current says "Subject: English, imperative present tense...". With helper it becomes "Subject: English, imperative present tense...". Good.

So I can remove the `lang` variable and the inline subjectLangInstruction/bodyLangInstruction.

### Change 2: Extract shared text-block filter helper

Current extractText:
```typescript
function extractText(result: { content: Array<{ type: string; text?: string }> }): string {
  return result.content
    .filter(
      (c): c is { type: "text"; text: string } =>
        c.type === "text" && !!c.text,
    )
    .map((c) => c.text)
    .join("\n")
    .trim();
}
```

Current extractAssistantContext has similar logic but with structural casts.

I can create:
```typescript
function extractTextBlocks(
  blocks: ReadonlyArray<unknown>,
): { type: "text"; text: string }[] {
  return blocks.filter(
    (c): c is { type: "text"; text: string } =>
      typeof c === "object" &&
      c !== null &&
      (c as { type?: string }).type === "text" &&
      !!(c as { text?: string }).text,
  );
}
```

Then extractText becomes:
```typescript
function extractText(result: { content: Array<{ type: string; text?: string }> }): string {
  return extractTextBlocks(result.content)
    .map((c) => c.text)
    .join("\n")
    .trim();
}
```

Wait, extractText currently uses `c.type === "text"` where `c` is typed as `{ type: string; text?: string }`. The new helper uses `typeof c === "object" && c !== null && ...` which is more defensive. For extractText, the input is already typed so this is fine.

